**Goal:**

Record audio from phone for 8 continuous hours while application is in the background and the phone is closed. In the event of audio interruptions (phone calls, alarms, music, etc.), pause recording during interruption and then resume upon end of interruption.

**Problem:**

The Expo AV library pauses recording upon interruption and does not resume. Background code execution must be handled natively not in Javascript.

**Framework Details:**

Initially Expo managed workflow. Now ejected to ExpoKit project.

**Attempted Solution:**

Modify behavior with minimal amount of written native code by modifying the native modules of the react native library Expo AV.

**Further Info:**

Hello,

I was working on an building an iOS application that is meant to record long audio sessions (~4-8 hours) in the background and when the phone is closed. Expo&#39;s AV library works fine for initiating recording and continuing to record in the background, however whenever there is an audio interruption (phone call, alarm, music), the recording pauses and does not resume recording after the interruption ends. 

I was initially working in an Expo managed workflow, but have since ejected to an ExpoKit project to give me more flexibility with the native implementation.

Initially I was hoping to handle the interruption in react native and resume the recording without the user having to re-open the application, but react native is not currently equipped to reliably execute background code. Instead, I am attempting to modify the [native objective-c modules for the Expo AV library][1] to handle the audio interruption natively (so that it can occur in the background).

It seems according to [this post][2], I should be following [Apple&#39;s built-in audio interruption handling][3]. I&#39;ve tried modifying the `handleAudioSessionInterruption` method in the EXAV.m implementation, but have not managed to alter the default behavior.

```lang-objective-c
- (void)handleAudioSessionInterruption:(NSNotification *)notification
{
  NSNumber *interruptionType = [[notification userInfo] objectForKey:AVAudioSessionInterruptionTypeKey];
  if (interruptionType.unsignedIntegerValue == AVAudioSessionInterruptionTypeBegan) {
    _currentAudioSessionMode = EXAVAudioSessionModeInactive;
  }
  
  if (interruptionType.unsignedIntegerValue == AVAudioSessionInterruptionTypeEnded) {
    _currentAudioSessionMode = EXAVAudioSessionModeActive;
  }
  
  [self _runBlockForAllAVObjects:^(NSObject&lt;EXAVObject&gt; *exAVObject) {
    [exAVObject handleAudioSessionInterruption:notification];
  }];
}
```

Expo provides an example implementation of the recording library [here][4].

If someone with more experience in iOS development and objective-c could chime in and maybe provide direction on where I should be focusing my efforts, that would be incredibly helpful.


  [1]: https://github.com/expo/expo/tree/master/packages/expo-av/ios/EXAV
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/54169447/avaudiorecorder-how-to-recover-from-incoming-call
  [3]: https://developer.apple.com/library/archive/documentation/Audio/Conceptual/AudioSessionProgrammingGuide/HandlingAudioInterruptions/HandlingAudioInterruptions.html
