It took me some noticeable time to figure out how to call `registerBufferProtocol` properly with Electron 7.0, so sharing this with the community and my future self.

According to Electron&#39;s [Breaking changes](https://github.com/electron/electron/blob/7-0-x/docs/api/breaking-changes-ns.md) document, `registerBufferProtocol` is now synchronous, so calling it has actually got simpler:

```
  electron.protocol.registerBufferProtocol(MY_PROTOCOL,
    (request, callback) =&gt; {
      const uri = request.url;
      if (uri) {
        callback({ mimeType: &#39;text/plain&#39;, data: Buffer.from(uri) });
      }
      else {
        callback({ error: -324 }); // EMPTY_RESPONSE
      }
    });
```

The confusing (to me) part of the warning was that the `callback` is actually **not** the `callback` arg to the `handler`, but rather is the last `completion` arg passed to the [`protocol.registerBufferProtocol`](https://electronjs.org/docs/api/protocol#protocolregisterbufferprotocolscheme-handler-completion) API itself.

